This function iterates through your line list, collecting continuous blocks of text until it encounters a separator or runs out of lines. It handles two modes: using explicit blank lines as breaks, or detecting paragraph boundaries via indentation.

```python
def _join_paragraphs(cls, lines, use_indent=False, leading_blanks=False, trailing_blanks=False):
        """Join adjacent lines together into paragraphs using either a blank line or indent as separator."""

        curr_para = []
        paragraphs = []

        for line in lines:
            if use_indent:
                if line.startswith(' '):
                    curr_para.append(line.lstrip())
                    continue
                elif line == '':
                    continue
                else:
                    if len(curr_para) > 0:
                        paragraphs.append(cls._join_paragraph(curr_para, leading_blanks, trailing_blanks))

                    curr_para = [line.lstrip()]
            else:
                if len(line) != 0:
                    curr_para.append(line)
                else:
                    paragraphs.append(cls._join_paragraph(curr_para, leading_blanks, trailing_blanks))
                    curr_para = []

        # Finish the last paragraph if there is one
        if len(curr_para) > 0:
            paragraphs.append(cls._join_paragraph(curr_para, leading_blanks, trailing_blanks))

        return paragraphs
```

Note how the code uses flags like trailing_blanks and leading_blanks to control the final appearance of the resulting paragraphs based on spacing needs.
